e’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Dev ."],"variants":[{"name":"Deborah","meanings":["Biblical name (meaning ‘bee’ in Hebrew), borne by the nurse of Rebecca (Genesis 35:8) and by a woman judge and prophet (Judges 4–5) who led the Israelites to victory over the Canaanites. It has always been popular as a Jewish name. It was in use among Christians by the mid 16th century and was taken up by the Puritans in the 17th century, in part because the bee was a symbol of industriousness. Since then it has enjoyed enormous popularity, peaking in the 1960s. Among other famous bearers is the actress  Deborah Kerr  (  1921–2007 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"William de Fraunceys was born about 1256, in Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Johannes Le Fraunceys. He had at least 1 son with Alice de Tykenhall. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"abt 1256–":"umbes 1256–Surnud","1256–Male":"1256–Surnud","1270–Female":"1270–Surnud","1304–1391":"1304–1391","1234–1288":"1234–1288","1304":"1304","1234":"1234","1256":"1256","1288":"1288","1391":"1391","1270":"1270","abt 1256":"umbes 1256","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Foremark, Burton Upon Trent, Derbyshire, England":"Foremark, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"abt 1256–":"noin 1256–Kuollut","1256–Male":"1256–Kuollut","1270–Female":"1270–Kuollut","1304–1391":"1304–1391","1234–1288":"1234–1288","1304":"1304","1234":"1234","1256":"12